\cf2 The implementation that allows the user to shoot snowballs by pressing the control key is the one that I am most proud of. To do this I created a method called scrollRight that only acts on Snowball images. To do so instead starting my loop from the left side of the grid I started it from the right and moved the snowball images across the screen that way. The trouble with this was that I wanted the snowballs to not only make a trap disappear when it hit it but also have itself disappear while not affecting the movement of any other items. This proved to be quite difficult as when I had the snowballs move they would act as the player and remove all the items they hit from the screen. I eventually figured out that I needed to provide code both in the scrollLeft and scrollRight methods because both had code affecting which images appeared on the screen. A few of my other implementations are as follows. I added collision methods for each object that each behaved in different ways when the user ran into a given image. For traps, the user\'92s magic dust would be set to 0, the time remaining would be decreased by 50 and the game speed would increase. Also if the user had the SnowMan power up the user\'92s Image would be changed from SnowMan to magicMan, losing the power-up. For Clocks and magic dust, time would be increased by 25 and magic dust would be increased by 1, respectively. For snowflakes, the users image would be changed to Snowman and the game speed would be decreased. For frogs, if the user had 5 clumps of magic dust the frog image would be removed and one of the three person images would be chosen and placed behind the user (The number of saves would also increase by 1). I also changed the win conditions for the games as it only has a timer now with an overarching goal of saving ten people from life as a frog but also has a component of trying to get the highest score possible.\
